Buffer output with time-based debouncing.

## Design
```go
// internal/streaming/buffer.go

type OutputBuffer struct {
    content     strings.Builder
    lastContent string           // For deduplication
    lastFlush   time.Time
    minInterval time.Duration    // Min time between flushes
    onFlush     func(string) error
    mu          sync.Mutex
    flushTimer  *time.Timer
    stopChan    chan struct{}
}

func NewOutputBuffer(minInterval time.Duration, onFlush func(string) error) *OutputBuffer

// Append adds new content (replaces previous - expects full content each time)
func (b *OutputBuffer) Append(content string) error {
    // 1. Update content
    // 2. If enough time since last flush, flush immediately
    // 3. Otherwise, schedule delayed flush
}

// flush sends current content to onFlush callback
func (b *OutputBuffer) flush() error {
    // Skip if content unchanged (deduplication)
    // Call onFlush with current content
    // Update lastFlush time
}

// Stop cancels any pending flush
func (b *OutputBuffer) Stop()
```

## Behavior
1. First append: Flush immediately
2. Rapid appends: Debounce, only flush every minInterval
3. Content unchanged: Skip flush (deduplication)
4. Stop called: Cancel pending timer

## Example Timeline (minInterval=500ms)
```
t=0ms:    Append("Hello")    -> Flush immediately
t=100ms:  Append("Hello W")  -> Schedule flush for t=500ms
t=200ms:  Append("Hello Wo") -> Reschedule flush for t=500ms
t=300ms:  Append("Hello Wor")-> Reschedule flush for t=500ms
t=500ms:  Timer fires        -> Flush "Hello Wor"
t=700ms:  Append("Hello World") -> Schedule flush for t=1000ms
```

